</CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">I/BNK I/IAV M/FCL N/DJN N/ENTR N/GEN N/HLT N/POV N/WER N/WLA R/NME R/NY R/US R/USE </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">NWREGULAR WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday SB119038352400065136594045841157604969071761 Massimo, Charles SYND CODES_REVIEWED Wires Wealth Management </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Markets</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Work With Special-Needs Families Underscores the Value of Planning; Focus on goals, flexibility for reality are key when addressing these families'—and all clients'—challenges</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Charles Massimo is chief executive of CJM Wealth Management in Deer Park, N.Y. Voices is an occasional feature of edited excerpts in which wealth managers address issues of interest to the advisory community. As told to Alex Coppola.</Para><Para>As the father of two boys with autism, helping special-needs families manage their financial planning isn't simply a professional challenge—it's one that I'm living myself. That understanding has allowed me to not only identify with clients in these situations, but also provide them with guidance and solutions drawn from my own experience as a parent.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Raising a child with autism can be taxing, both emotionally and financially. From therapy to education and housing, the costs associated with a child's care and development are significant—and, by and large, those costs are the responsibility of the child's parents. For example, while federal funding provides many younger autistic children with access to basic speech and physical-therapy programs, those children often require additional therapies that aren't subsidized and may be only partially covered by a family's insurance. Alternative medicines and therapies that may be used to complement traditional services must be paid for out of pocket.</Para><Para>For autistic individuals over the age of 21, public services—particularly housing—is even harder to come by. Group homes have waiting lists of up to 10 years, which presses many parents into service as full-time caregivers.</Para><Para>Part of advisers' responsibility is educating and building a support system around parents with autistic children, which includes helping them identify and explore available resources. Advisers should want them to take full advantage of any support they are entitled to and to develop an awareness of the kind responsibility they'll need to shoulder on their own. That understanding is critical to a client's ability to plan and make informed decisions for their family.</Para><Para>Parents of autistic children are engaged in a demanding juggling act, managing the steep cost of their child's development and well-being without dropping the ball on their own financial needs. One of the keys to keeping all of those balls in the air is the establishment of a comprehensive financial plan and a commitment on the client's part to see it through. My firm begins that planning process by assessing the needs and goals of every family member—education, housing, retirement—and then creating separate savings buckets that are to be used exclusively for accomplishing each.</Para><Para>This is similar to the planning process used with all clients. Under these circumstances, though, the partitioning of funds is particularly important. Otherwise, every parent's impulse is to put their children's needs first, and when the cost of those needs is staggeringly high, it's easy for them to lose sight of their future and exhaust the savings required to provide for their own care.</Para><Para>Maybe the greatest challenge facing these families is the fact that autism is ever-changing. Children and their needs can and do shift dramatically, even from one year to the next. And while that uncertainty might seem to render planning futile, it reinforces its importance. It's forethought and structure that gives these families the flexibility to they need to accommodate for, and safeguard themselves against, unforeseen challenges. Regardless of whether you work with families affected by autism, every adviser can learn something from that approach.</Para><Para>We have to push ourselves as advisers to ask more questions, to revisit strategies more actively, and to be more thorough in uncovering what our clients care most deeply about and ensuring we're doing our best to protect it.</Para><Para>More Voices</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-integrating-processes-into-crm-systems-can-improve-client-service-1521558002?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=10">How Integrating Processes Into CRM Systems Can Improve Client Service</ELink> (March 20, 2018)</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/going-beyond-the-numbers-asking-the-right-questions-of-clients-1521472999?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=1">Going Beyond the Numbers: Asking Clients the Right Questions</ELink> (March 19, 2018)</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-successful-succession-planning-must-factor-in-growth-1520953201?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=1">Why Successful Succession Planning Must Factor In Growth</ELink> (March 13, 2018)</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-estate-tax-changes-wont-diminish-clients-philanthropy-1520866802?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=1">Why Estate-Tax Changes Won't Diminish Clients' Philanthropy</ELink> (March 12, 2018)</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-to-harness-mental-accounting-to-instill-good-financial-habits-1520525923?mod=WSJ_WealthAdviser_W